04964nam a22006855i 9780228019138DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280191387 a10.1515/97802280191382doi  a(DE-B1597)658174  a(OCoLC)1372155322  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1993.5.G3bP45 2023 7aPER0041602bisacsh04a791.430943/155223  aAP 449112rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7516:6681 aPfleger, Simone, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUntimely Bodies, Untimely Aesthetics :bTemporality, Relationality, and Intimacy in the Cinema of the Berlin School /cSimone Pfleger. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource :b31 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Translation -- tTemporality and the Cinema of the Berlin School -- tOf Becoming Untimely -- tTenuous Relations and Fleeting Connections -- tOf Homes and Families -- tQueer Affinities and Fantasies of Relationality -- tChampioning the Now and/or Moving Onward towards a Then? -- tNotes -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile heteronormativity continues to permeate nearly all threads of the socio-cultural fabric, several early twenty-first-century German films offer insight into how we might challenge that dominance and disrupt its linear construction of time.Examining the fluidity of time in eight contemporary films of the Berlin School, Untimely Bodies, Untimely Aesthetics foregrounds how queer conceptualizations of temporality can engage notions of subjectivity, relationality, and intimacy in visual representations. Each film depicts figures that grapple with an unattainable desire for connection, placed in landscapes shaped by hegemonic heteronormative intimacies, and a linear temporal organization of life that conforms to mainstream, traditional rhythms, and milestones. Simone Pfleger proposes a new model for viewing non-normative relationality and intimacies, using the concept of untimeliness as an analytical framework for examining content and aesthetics. In these films, untimeliness provides an alternative to the romanticization of progress by charting how the filmic figures understand themselves and relate to one another in various spheres: work, love, sex, home, family, and self. Ultimately, Pfleger shows how the texts uncover a temporary promise of breaking free from restrictive social structures, even as they make clear that this schism cannot and should not be permanent.By proposing time as a critical lens through which to investigate our relationships and intimacies, Untimely Bodies, Untimely Aesthetics offers a new way to think about film and encourages moviegoers to turn the analysis back toward themselves and their own desires, expectations, assumptions, and adherence to or deviation from normative narratives in their own lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInterpersonal relations in motion pictures. 0aIntimacy (Psychology) in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy21st century. 0aTime in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Regional & National.2bisacsh  abodies.  adesire.  afamily.  afilm.  agender.  aheteronormativity.  amonogamy.  aneoliberalism.  aqueerness.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228019138?locatt=mode:legacy4